<p class="p">As illustrated above the liquid contact angle in air can be predicted from Yong’s equation, the contact angle of liquid a (
 <italic class="italic">l</italic>
 <sub class="sub">a</sub>) in liquid b (
 <italic class="italic">l</italic>
 <sub class="sub">b</sub>) cannot be calculated from Young’s equation. In order to explain the wetting behaviors of liquid a on solid surface in liquid b and calculate the liquid a contact angle under liquid b (
 <italic class="italic">θ</italic>
 <sub class="sub">LaCA</sub>), the following equation has been derived from Young’s equation [
 <xref rid="B30-polymers-11-00806" ref-type="bibr" class="xref">30</xref>,
 <xref rid="B85-polymers-11-00806" ref-type="bibr" class="xref">85</xref>,
 <xref rid="B86-polymers-11-00806" ref-type="bibr" class="xref">86</xref>]: 
 <disp-formula id="FD5-polymers-11-00806" class="disp-formula">
  <label class="label">(5)</label>
  <math id="mm5" class="math">
   <mrow class="mrow">
    <mrow class="mrow">
     <mi class="mi">cos</mi>
     <msub class="msub">
      <mi class="mi">θ</mi>
      <mrow class="mrow">
       <msub class="msub">
        <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">L</mi>
        <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">a</mi>
       </msub>
       <mi class="mi">CA</mi>
      </mrow>
     </msub>
     <mo class="mo">=</mo>
     <mfrac class="mfrac">
      <mrow class="mrow">
       <msub class="msub">
        <mi class="mi">γ</mi>
        <mrow class="mrow">
         <msub class="msub">
          <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">l</mi>
          <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">a</mi>
         </msub>
         <mtext class="mtext">-</mtext>
         <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">g</mi>
        </mrow>
       </msub>
       <mi class="mi">cos</mi>
       <msub class="msub">
        <mi class="mi">θ</mi>
        <mi class="mi">a</mi>
       </msub>
       <mo class="mo">−</mo>
       <msub class="msub">
        <mi class="mi">γ</mi>
        <mrow class="mrow">
         <msub class="msub">
          <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">l</mi>
          <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">b</mi>
         </msub>
         <mtext class="mtext">-</mtext>
         <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">g</mi>
        </mrow>
       </msub>
       <mi class="mi">cos</mi>
       <msub class="msub">
        <mi class="mi">θ</mi>
        <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">b</mi>
       </msub>
      </mrow>
      <mrow class="mrow">
       <msub class="msub">
        <mi class="mi">γ</mi>
        <mrow class="mrow">
         <msub class="msub">
          <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">l</mi>
          <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">a</mi>
         </msub>
         <mtext class="mtext">-</mtext>
         <msub class="msub">
          <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">l</mi>
          <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">b</mi>
         </msub>
        </mrow>
       </msub>
      </mrow>
     </mfrac>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </disp-formula> where 
 <italic class="italic">γ</italic>
 <sub class="sub">l
  <sub class="sub">a</sub>-g
 </sub>, 
 <italic class="italic">γ</italic>
 <sub class="sub">l
  <sub class="sub">b</sub>-g
 </sub> and 
 <italic class="italic">γ</italic>
 <sub class="sub">l
  <sub class="sub">a</sub>-l
  <sub class="sub">b</sub>
 </sub> are interface tensions of liquid a-gas, liquid b-gas and liquid a-liquid b interface, respectively. 
 <italic class="italic">θ</italic>
 <sub class="sub">a</sub> and 
 <italic class="italic">θ</italic>
 <sub class="sub">b</sub> are the contact angle of liquid a and liquid a in air, respectively. (
 <xref ref-type="fig" rid="polymers-11-00806-f006" class="xref">Figure 6</xref>a)
</p>
